This is a known breaking change in **.NET 10 MAUI**. Android's `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` was deprecated in API 30, and .NET 10 adopts **edge-to-edge** rendering by default, so `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` no longer shrinks the window.

Here's how to fix it for a chat UI with a bottom-pinned input bar:

### 1. AndroidManifest.xml — keep `adjustResize`

```xml
<activity ... android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" />
```

This still dispatches **window insets** even though it no longer physically resizes the window.

### 2. React to keyboard insets on Android

Create a small platform behavior that listens for IME insets and applies bottom padding:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/KeyboardInsetBehavior.cs
#if ANDROID
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;

public static class KeyboardInsetBehavior
{
    public static void Attach(Layout rootLayout)
    {
        rootLayout.HandlerChanged += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (rootLayout.Handler?.PlatformView is Android.Views.View nativeView)
            {
                ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(nativeView, new KeyboardInsetsListener(rootLayout));
            }
        };
    }

    private class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        private readonly Layout _layout;

        public KeyboardInsetsListener(Layout layout) => _layout = layout;

        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var density = DeviceDisplay.MainDisplayInfo.Density;

            // Convert px → DIPs and set bottom padding so input floats above keyboard
            _layout.Padding = new Thickness(0, 0, 0, imeInsets.Bottom / density);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
#endif
```

### 3. Wire it up in your chat page

```xml
<!-- ChatPage.xaml -->
<Grid x:Name="RootGrid" RowDefinitions="*,Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" ... />

    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

```csharp
// ChatPage.xaml.cs
public ChatPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();
#if ANDROID
    KeyboardInsetBehavior.Attach(RootGrid);
#endif
}
```

### Why this works

| .NET 9 | .NET 10 (edge-to-edge) |
|---|---|
| `Resize` shrank the window | Window stays full-screen; keyboard is an **inset** |
| Layout auto-adjusted | You read `Ime()` insets and apply padding yourself |

**iOS** already handles this correctly via `adjustResize`-equivalent behavior built into UIKit, so no platform code is needed there.

**Tip:** If you're inside a `ScrollView`, MAUI's built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` will auto-scroll to the focused `Entry`—but for a bottom-pinned chat bar, the inset approach above is what you want.
